  "opinion": "As a 48-year-old barista in Kansas City, married with four kids and dealing with depression, I spend hours daily on social media, so fake content is a real headache for me. With my high openness from the OCEAN traits, I'm curious and like to explore different views, but that also means I see a lot of nonsense online. My low agreeableness makes me skeptical, so I don't just believe everything I read. Managing fake content starts with checking sources—I look for trusted news or official sites, especially since my parents have higher education, which taught me to value facts. My moderate conscientiousness helps me take a moment to think before sharing, avoiding spreading lies. I also use tools like fact-checking websites, though with primary school education, I keep it simple. My Islamic beliefs guide me to seek truth and avoid harm, so I report fake posts that could hurt others. Knitting and reading novels give me patience to sift through information, and my depression means I avoid stressful fake news that worsens my mood. I talk to my family about what we see online, teaching my kids to be careful too. It's about staying alert, using common sense, and not letting fake stuff ruin my day or mislead others.",
